Inflation in Europe has slipped on food
Accelerated inflation, measured in the euro area, is mainly due to the rapid rise in food prices.
In November, the price increase in the 13 euro area countries was larger than expected, after an inflation rate of 2.6 per cent in October, an annual inflation of 3.1 per cent was recorded, said the European Community statistics office in Luxembourg.
Official forecasts indicated only 3 percent, Bloomberg said.
Unlike the U.S., British and Canadian central banks, the European Central Bank (ECB) has not lowered the policy interest rate by saying that falling interest rates, along with rising commodity prices and falling unemployment, would lead to the generation of an inflationary spiral.
The ECB would like to keep the inflation rate below but close to two percent.
According to one analyst, it is catch 22 for the ECB: "we must deter" inflation so that we no longer have to intervene on this subject later.
In Germany, the inflation rate of 3.3 per cent is a record over the last twelve years and in Spain it has risen from 3.6 to 4.1.
Inflation in the euro area has taken off due to the rapid rise in food and energy prices.
Cereal futures market shares increased by 88 percent and soybean prices also reached their highest value since 1973.
The price of food oil and dairy products also increased significantly in 2007.
This year, the world oil price rose by 52 percent, and last month, a barrel of black gold cost nearly $100.
According to the ECB, in 2008 the inflation rate will rise from 2.1 per cent this year to 2.5 per cent, but in 2009 it will fall to 1.9 per cent.
According to analysts, the 12-month inflation rate remains around 3 percent, however, for the next 3 to 4 months, the annual average rate will be 2.1 percent.
At the same time, they expect the ECB to lower the policy rate twice in 2008.
Gallup warns of government crisis
After a long stagnation, the number of supporters of the Fidesz (Alliance of Young Democrats) increased significantly at the beginning of December, so since 2002, it currently has the largest number of supporters, while Gallup (Survey Institute) has never before seen such low socialist support, namely 13 percent.
For loyal voters, the difference would represent, due to the greater determination of the opposition voters, a support of more than two-thirds (71 percent) against the support of a fifth (20 percent) for the MSZP (Hungarian Socialist Party).
According to the poll, the MDF (Hungarian Democratic Forum) and the SZDSZ (Alliance of Free Democrats) are below the threshold of parliamentarians: their support is two percent across the population.
On faithful voters certain to go and vote, the number of supporters of both parties increased by 1 percent.
The economic climate has continued to deteriorate compared to the previous low point, the proportion of those who considered the economic situation in the country to be particularly dire has never been higher, it rises to 41 per cent and according to 46 per cent additionally the situation is quite dire.
After the more optimistic prospects of last spring and summer, families are once again more pessimistic about their financial situation.
For next year, the majority of the population expects a worsening and only a tenth expects an improvement in the situation.
Last December, 71 percent of those surveyed, a majority never seen in Gallup’s previous polls, said the prime minister was doing his job rather badly than well.
13 percent of respondents have confidence or a lot of confidence in Ferenc Gyurcs<0xC3><0xA1>ny while 38 percent support Viktor Orb<0xC3><0xA1>n.
54 percent do not trust the prime minister at all and 27 percent do not trust the president of Fidesz.
One of the indicators of the change in the political situation is the proportion of society that believes that discontent with the Prime Minister can be addressed without a change in government.
While after the October riots, 35 per cent of respondents wanted the government and the prime minister to remain in office, this rate currently stands at only 20 per cent, with the relative majority (33 per cent) believing that holding new elections would be the solution to this situation.
When asked about the intention to vote, 60 percent of respondents said they would certainly vote and the additional 20 percent said they would probably vote.
To make the comparison, for a "legislative election to be held next Sunday", only 55 percent of the respondents would certainly participate and 15 percent would probably supplement them. According to current intentions, the result of the referendum would be in no doubt.
74 percent of people would say no to enrolment fees in higher education, 79 percent would say no to consultation fees and 84 percent would say no to hospital stay fees.
When we look only at the same proportions among people who expressed their intention to vote in the referendum, respectively 81, 84 and 89 percent of voters would reject the introduction of registration fees, consultation fees and hospital stay fees.
Auchan is the most expensive, Tesco has raised its prices by almost twenty percent
The hypermarkets in Budaörs' commercial triangle maintained last year's average price increase of 16 percent, with the difference that this year's VAT rate did not rise.
Article by Napi Gazdas<0xC3><0xA1>g (Daily Economy)
This year, in the Budaörs trade triangle, the usual daily Christmas basket also increased by an average of 16 percent, a value increase of well over a thousand forints was displayed in all hypermarkets.
Prices, "which had already soared" in grocery stores last December, did not rise sharply from the previous high base.
Nonetheless, consumers are obviously shocked to see that items purchased significantly below nine thousand forints last year now cost more than ten thousand forints.
The daily shopping basket in the surveyed hypermarkets exceeded the psychological threshold of ten thousand forints by at least 91 forints.
And the highest value of the basket was 10,573 forints.
(In 2003, this value was 6,800 forints.)
Prices for Unicum and live fish remained almost at last year's level, but prices for turkey fillet, nuts and poppy have risen sharply.
In the stores, the price of flour and bread followed the data of the KSH (Central Institute of Statistics) but, in Auchan, bread was found from one kilo to only 139 forints.
Competition did not lower the price of the product below 200 forints.
It was amazing to see, also in this hypermarket, that the price of the two-litre bottle of Coca-Cola was below 200 forints, so it only cost 257 forints per bottle of Coca-Cola included.
However, this year, in terms of Daily Basket, Auchan was the most expensive and Cora the cheapest.
According to our calculations, Cora increased the price of its Daily Basket by 15 percent while Tesco and Auchan increased them by about 18 and 18 percent respectively.
Comparing last year's most expensive basket with this year's cheapest basket, we see a gap of 12 percent while the difference between last year's cheapest and this year's most expensive is 21 percent.
Prices increased by an average of 1,480 forints.
Last year, prices rose by an average of 1,206 forints, knowing that the impact of the VAT rate increase was already being noticed in last year's Christmas prices.
This process perplexed trade, as hypermarkets could not visibly determine which margin to apply to products because they were unable to predict the impact of price change on consumption.
(If a trader miscalculates the rotation of a product, he risks losing a large profit on the margin adapted to the intensity of the trade.)
Due to the change in the VAT rate, the daily basket price increase has evolved so excessively that the most expensive basket was 1,720 forints higher than the value of the 2006 one, while the difference between the cheapest baskets was only 844 forints.
This year, the difference was not so excessive since the value of the most expensive basket was 1,630 forints higher than last year and the prices of the cheapest forint increased by 1,284 forints as well.
As we approached the two Christmas seasons, we saw a catastrophic increase in prices, in less than 20 months the prices of everyday consumer items increased by more than 30 percent in hypermarkets.
(This does not necessarily confirm the KSH data: for some basic supplies, the Institute of Statistics has observed a price increase of more than 30 per cent in 12 months.
This is the case, for example, with flour and egg.)
According to the Daily Basket of the latter, this seems almost absurd since the price level of this product, already very expensive last year, has increased by just more than 10 percent compared to the base.
According to the indices, flour suppliers are in a stronger position than egg suppliers because they have managed to make the sudden increase in prices also accepted by multinationals.
In the commercial golden triangle, hypermarkets do not complain, they constantly record good years.
In our experience, the majority of customers no longer look at prices in the three hypermarkets visited.
They buy everything in quantity, they take long-preserved foods by pallets.
On Wednesday morning, important queues were formed at the checkouts of the three hypermarkets as the number of customers increased sharply.
However, according to our information, the turnover is less important in the province, many multinationals complain to the survey companies that they do not even reach the expected turnover, not only for food but also for articles of sustainable consumption.
Many hospitals are saving on disinfectants
This year, more than a thousand infections, mainly caused by the incorrect use of antibiotics, have been registered in hospitals.
The hygienic conditions of hospitals, the insufficient number of beds, the overwork of medical staff do not help to block infections, says the chief doctor of the National Center for Epidemiology.
Many hospitals are also saving on disinfectants
Not long ago a MRSA infection was diagnosed in the traumatology department of J<0xC3><0xA1>nos Hospital.
The antibiotic-resistant bacterium was detected in a man hospitalized following a serious accident.
The patient was isolated.
At the beginning of the year a similar infection occurred in the same place.
The person injured in a serious car accident was discharged from the hospital but soon after had to return to the hospital due to a MRSA infection and, since then, doctors have not been able to perform a major operation because of the bacteria in his body.
Until 10 December this year, 1,094 hospital infections generated by a multi-resistant pathogen were reported to the National Hospital Surveillance System, said Karolina Böröcz, chief physician at the National Epidemiology Centre.
To know that it is the number of infections caused by a multi-resistant pathogen that has actually been registered in hospitals and for the rest we have no information.
Approximately two-thirds of infections (683 infections) were caused by MRSA, i.e. methicillin-oxacillin-resistant staphylococcus aureus.
A third of people carry the Staphylococcus aureus (SA) bacteria in their noses without it developing a disease.
Infections caused by AS (such as angina, tonsillitis, skin infections, traumatic infections) react well to antibiotics, they are easily curable.
However, if antibiotics are used excessively or inappropriately, the bacterium, which reacts well to antibiotics, will develop a well-resistant bacterium that will proliferate quickly in poor hospital conditions.
In case of temporary or prolonged malfunction of the immune system, this bacterium can cause serious hospital infections, such as traumatic infection or sepsis, in elderly, underweight or weakened patients.
According to the head doctor of J<0xC3><0xA1>nos Hospital, there is nothing special about MRSA infections, these infections are part of the daily lives of hospitals.
We should not confuse the infection with the epidemic, we do not find MRSA only the one where we do not look for them, said Tibor Nyulasi.
SAs are resistant to antibiotics.
“These patients are isolated, the caregivers put on rubber gloves and protective masks and we have antibiotics adapted to treat them,” said Tibor Nyulasi.
A priori, hospitalized patients are examined if they are MRSA carriers, however infection cannot always be avoided.
Sampling is not fashionable
The vast majority of infections caused by MRSA could be prevented, but current conditions and circumstances in Hungarian hospitals are not conducive to preventing the development and proliferation of multidrug-resistant pathogens, says Karolina Böröcz.
Since this infection is most common in hospitals and nursing homes, hospitals should monitor hospitalized patients and immediately isolate patients with MRSA.
However, microbiological sampling is not fashionable in Hungarian hospitals.
It should be noted that the National Social Security Fund does not fund these examinations.
Most cases arise only if the MRSA infection is detectable on the patient, said the chief doctor of the epidemiological center.
The European Union has stringent recommendations for the appropriate use of antibiotics in human medicine and there are also Hungarian guidelines for the cure of certain infections and syndromes.
Efforts must be made to ensure that antibiotic therapy is targeted, in other words microbiological tests should be carried out to prevent drug resistance, but hospitals do not always take this into account.
Microbiological sampling is even rarer in outpatient care and basic care, said Karolina Böröcz.
Many hospitals are saving on disinfectants
Scientific evidence shows that MRSA proliferates from one patient to another most often through medical personnel.
It is therefore essential to wash your hands, put on gloves and protective masks, but important gaps are detected in hospitals also in this area.
MRSAs proliferate by infection transmitted by inhalation of droplets and by contact. However, due to conditions in Hungarian hospitals, the infected patient cannot always be isolated.
In addition, the rooms are often full, the beds are often too close to each other while in terms of epidemic, the patients should be at least 1.5 meters away from each other.
Unfortunately, we also find that hospitals, in a difficult financial situation, are saving on disinfectants, they lack nurses, there are many sick people, so the risk of contamination is even greater, said Karolina Böröcz.
According to Karolina Böröcz, in hospitals where preventive measures are followed, the number of infections is demonstrably lower or the proliferation of the pathogen can be blocked.
Government project against MRSA
The treatment of MRSA infection is an exorbitant expense for social security funds, which is why this infection is being fought everywhere.
In England, for example, the government has established a program to prevent or reduce the incidence of MRSA.
According to published data, this program is effective and MRSA infections show a decreasing trend in England.
The European Centre for Disease Prevention and Control (ECDC) has identified the prevention of the incidence of multidrug-resistant pathogens (such as MRSA) as well as the prevention of hospital infections caused by these pathogens as one of its priorities.
The Commissioner, the author of a fatal accident, was not intoxicated.
The official statement regarding the fatal accident caused by the Commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement has been drawn up.
It can be excluded that the commissioner of the 22nd arrondissement, resigning from his post since, who crushed a pedestrian causing his death last Tuesday, would have driven in a state of drunkenness or dizziness, Attila Morvai, spokesman for the public prosecutor's office of the capital, said Friday after the relative finding was established.
The finding confirmed the first result of the investigation, which already found that the former commissioner had not consumed alcohol before he got behind the wheel.
Last Tuesday, the former head of the police station in the 22nd arrondissement crushed a 55-year-old man who was in front of him when he turned, with his personal car, in Kossuth Lajos street in the 22nd arrondissement. The man wanted to cross the road by not passing through the pedestrian crossing.
(By the way, the fact that he crossed the road outside the pedestrian crossing is not an extenuating circumstance, according to the Highway Code a car that starts a turn must let pedestrians pass.)
The pedestrian died after being transported to the hospital.
Following this accident, the Commissioner resigned from his position and requested his retirement because, according to the police communication, this accident upset him a lot.
The investigation into this case is being conducted by the Budapest Public Prosecutor's Office.
Attila Morvai also mentioned that the former commissioner cooperated from the beginning with the magistrates in charge of the investigation.
Additional €400 million for infrastructure
J<0xC3><0xA1>nos Veres, Minister of Finance of Hungary, and Marta Gajecka, Vice-President of the European Investment Bank (EIB), signed on Friday in Budapest three agreements with a total value of 400 million euros for a credit line to support education, transport and environment infrastructure as well as energy.
In 2006, the European Investment Bank (EIB) adopted a budget of EUR 300 million for the Hungarian budgetary financing of transport and environmental projects to be carried out from the Cohesion Fund, of which a credit agreement worth EUR 100 million has already been signed by the parties. This time, the contract signed concerns the use of the remaining EUR 200 million.
