Bulgaria, a paradise for the EU real estate market
The development of the Bulgarian real estate market is spectacular, the attention of the whole of Europe is turned to this country of the Balkans little mentioned in the past.
What, or and who bought in this EU market which is always the cheapest but which will quickly become expensive?
Analysis of the Bulgarian division of Re/Max.
Currently, in real estate, Bulgaria is unquestionably the most fashionable target in Eastern Europe with its cheap ski apartments and seaside houses.
In the mountains, the most popular regions are Bansko, Borovec, Pamprovo and Vitosa and, by the sea, Albéna, the "Golden Sands", the "Sun Coast", the ancient Sozopol and Nessebar but they are increasingly looking for a building in the Kavarna and Balcik region as well.
According to analysts of Re/Max Bulgaria, sooner or later, the central region of the country, namely Veliko Tarnovo, Gabrovo, Elena, Triavna, will also arouse the interest of investors and they are also more and more to buy in the very cheap corner of Ruse.
Sofia, the capital, also offers attractive opportunities, with retail and office areas promising the highest depreciation rate.
Bulgaria is on track to become one of the most attractive golf paradises in Europe and thus be a priority destination, after the summer and winter season, also in the other two seasons of the year.
More vigilant investors already buy in large numbers, for example in the corner of Bansko.
According to analysts, people buying a building in Bulgaria are looking at the same time to change their life, their way of life.
Most of the buyers are English but others come from France, Belgium, Spain and more and more from Romania.
There are also Maltese and Cypriot investors. On the shores of the Black Sea and in the most famous ski resorts, we traditionally meet many Russian buyers.
Foreign buyers are divided into three groups, says Georgij Jankov, regional director of Re/Max Bulgaria.
People planning to settle buy renovated buildings, at a price ranging from 50 to 100 thousand euros, or old dilapidated houses, at a price ranging from 5 to 15 thousand euros, which are then renovated.
The criteria are easy access and communication possibilities, proximity to a large city, shops and in general that of the local doctor.
The second group includes buyers of second homes (since last December, Bulgaria is listed among the top 10 holiday destinations in Germany).
The third group is made up of commercial investors who buy in the hope of achieving medium- or long-term gains.
The price of buildings in the capital is constantly increasing due to an increasing demand.
In the European Union, real estate prices are the lowest in Bulgaria. However, in the last 5 years they have increased by 21 percent each year.
The increase in real estate prices essentially exceeds the increase in wages.
Fodor and the Six Percent Hungarians
According to the communication of G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, the meetings of the professionals are concluded on Tuesday, however, Wednesday, after the official opening, the negotiations of the ministers on the international climate regime after 2012 will continue.
Experts and politicians from 192 countries around the world will discuss the Bali Roadmap to define the efforts to be made after the Kyoto Protocol emission reduction period until 2012.
At the moment, there are intense discussions on this issue between developing and developed countries.
The United States also reported that, at the moment, it did not want to discuss exact figures, while it was ready to sign an agreement on reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 25 to 40 percent from the 1990 level until 2020.
Another important topic of the conference is whether developed countries are committed, apart from emission reductions, to providing financial and technological assistance to countries in need.
An agreement was also signed on aid to developing countries.
The aid fund defined by the Kyoto Protocol will be managed by a 16-member board of directors, likely under the UN Global Environment Facility (GEF), Piac és Profit (Market and Profit) said.
6 percent of Hungary
On behalf of Hungary, G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor, Minister of Environment and Water, confirms the EU's ambition to retain its role as flagship in global efforts to protect the climate and encourage the signing of the new international agreement by 2009.
The minister explained that the EU is committed to reducing its greenhouse gas emissions by 20 per cent from 1990 levels by 2020, regardless of the successful signing of the “Post-2012 Agreement”, and is ready to reduce them by up to 30 per cent if other major regions of the world and/or developing countries are also ready to make commitments tailored to their responsibilities.
G<0xC3><0xA1>bor Fodor recalled that in 1997, the signatory countries of the Kyoto Protocol had aimed for a total reduction of 5.2 per cent and all 15 EU members at that time made the commitment by 8 per cent less.
Hungary has made a commitment to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 6 percent compared to the level of the period between 1985 and 1987, our country will fulfill its commitment, recalls the press release of the Ministry of the Environment.
The stakes are high in Bali because the long-term international agreement on climate policy must be put in place within two years, otherwise the entry into force of the agreement would certainly be postponed after 2012. In this case, the pledges of reduction below the values envisaged in the Kyoto Protocol would not be immediately followed by a new international emission reduction system whose need was underlined in the new IPCC report.
The reduction of emissions would be delayed and the increase in the average temperature of the Earth of more than 2 degrees celcius could no longer be avoided, which, according to scientists, would have extremely serious and irrevocable consequences.
British Army recruits on YouTube
British army units are sharing footage from their operations in Iraq and Afghanistan on the video-sharing site with the aim of becoming popular.
First, it is the British Air Force (RAF) that has become passionate about YouTube: special units operating in Afghanistan upload video footage of operations against the Taliban since March 2006, the BBC reported.
These recordings, taken using miniature cameras mounted on the helmet, are monitored at Air Force Operations Headquarters in Kandahar and are then transferred to London or uploaded by compatriots to the Internet.
The political message is unavoidable
Air force soldiers have already passed 139 sequences on the net through this channel and their "chain" has been watched by more than 75,000 people.
The British Ministry of Defence signed up under the name "defenceheadquarters" in the spring of 2007 and is sharing videos on operations in Iraq and Afghanistan while the Commonwealth Office and the International Peacekeeping Forces in Iraq (MNFI) also have their own channels on YouTube.
Mission in Afghanistan
According to the initial objective of the air force, the videos were passed on the net to recruit. According to the Ministry of Defence, they also served to make the public aware of the real objectives of the presence of the army abroad.
The propaganda published through this channel costs almost nothing compared to the usual recruitment advertisements on television, Gordon Mackenzie, a defence consultant, told BBC News, but it also inevitably carries a political message since it justifies in a special way the merits of the military operations decided by the government.
The Americans played a game.
The army is annoyed because, apart from the carefully composed and censored videos, amateur videos are passed on the sharing site that also present, for example, the death of soldiers: in the "official" propaganda films, a little hypocritical, the officers do not avoid talking about the losses but they never present the bloody side of the fight.
In fact, many videos had already been passed on the net showing the areas of operations in Iraq and Afghanistan that were carried out on a real mission, but the British military has only recently become excited about uploading these videos.
The Americans do the recruitment a little differently by using the free downloadable shooting game America's Army. In this game the player can put himself directly in the place of the soldiers as part of a simulation more or less real.
