Banks want to solve the crisis
The U.S. Federal Reserve Bank, the European Central Bank and the British, Swiss and Canadian central banks have decided to fight the financial market crisis together.
More than a hundred billion dollars will be placed on the money markets through auctions.
The banks will have to sell, through an auction system, the interest rates at which they are willing to borrow money.
For example, the U.S. Fed will auction off $40 billion and provide $24 billion to the European and Swiss central banks.
This is the first time since the attacks of 11 September that the Central Banks of individual States have decided to take such concerted action, aimed at preventing or reducing the effects of the financial crisis.
"This approach tends to solve the major problems of the economy, namely the growing lack of free capital that banks could lend," Bernard Baumohl of the consulting firm Economic Outlook Group wrote in his report to clients.
“The concerted action of the central banks has reduced the probability of a recession in the United States from 65 percent to about 50 percent,” Baumohl added in his report.
Banks have already lost $60 billion due to unsecured loans, especially in the United States.
Analysts expect more losses in the billions.
"If the central banks have chosen this approach, it is because they really need to understand what can still follow," said ABN Chief Economist Amro Kieran Davies.
“It seems that the situation is really bad,” he adds.
The central banks fear that if the banks themselves have difficult access to loans, they will lend more to their customers.
This would reduce consumption and plunge the U.S. economy into a recession that could affect economic growth around the world.
The Central Banks made this choice after they failed to bring down the London interbank rate, called LIBOR, used to borrow on the interbank market.
This meant that banks were still afraid of mutual borrowing, despite the fact that the U.S., Canadian and British central banks repeatedly lowered their interest rates during the fall.
"This will have the same effect as a further drop in interest rates," Greg Salvaggio of Tempus Consulting told Reuters.
Some analysts don’t believe that the central bank’s approach will help ward off the crisis, since it doesn’t solve the main problem that is the fall of the U.S. housing market.
