In Afghanistan, Allies Are Passive, Say Americans
The lack of soldiers and necessary equipment influences, according to the United States, the course of the mission in Afghanistan.
According to Defence Minister Robert Gates, NATO should outline a concrete plan for the coming years.
The mission in Afghanistan is not proceeding as it should, representatives of the countries that have troops in the southern part of the country have agreed in Edinburgh, Scotland.
In addition to the growing protests from the Taliban movement, the eight states involved are also discussing future plans and allied coordination.
While the United States this week called on NATO troops through Defence Minister Robert Gates for greater activity, Britain sees as a priority the strengthening of the authority of the Afghan government and the intensification of development aid.
“The evolution in Afghanistan is perceptible, but military power can only be part of the solution.
The other is to allow residents to start a new development of the economy and security themselves," British Defence Minister Des Browne told the BBC.
Ninety percent
The activity of the Afghan insurgents is, according to US military data, the most intense in the last five years.
The number of violent actions increased by 27 percent from last year, to 60 percent in the southern province of Helmand.
NATO countries have about 40,000 troops in Afghanistan, nearly a quarter of them in the southern part.
However, according to the United States, the allies reached their absolute limit and in the organization and equipment of the troops.
Concretely, they are asking for other helicopters, soldiers and experts for the training of Afghan troops.
“We will need to think seriously about the concrete goals for the coming period, as well as how to achieve them,” Gates said.
