State debt to rise to 1 trillion in 2009
The burden of a state debt exceeding 84,000 kronor lies with each Czech.
The total debt rose at the end of September to 842.7 billion crowns.
The government had planned to borrow 159.2 billion crowns this year.
As a result of better-than-expected changes in state budget savings, the ministry reduced the projected amount to 152.8 billion kroner.
The debt of the State of the Czech Republic rose towards the end of September to 842.7 billion crowns.
During the nine months of this year it increased by 40.2 billion crowns.
However, as of June, it decreased by 13.4 billion crowns.
Today, the Ministry of Finance confirmed its data on the state debt dating from early October.
The burden of a debt exceeding 84,000 kronor lies with each Czech.
Over the past year, the state has indebted itself more than 111 billion kroner.
“For now, it seems that, thanks to a smaller deficit forecast for next year, we could cross the border by a trillion crowns only in 2009.
Next year, the debt is expected to be between $900 billion and $1 trillion," Patria Finance analyst David Marek told iHNed.cz.
Next Finance analyst Vladim<0xC3><0xAD>r Pikor’s forecast is similar: “We could exceed the trillion in the course of 2009.
The precise date will depend on the next budget that is not yet known.
If it appeared that the situation on the political scene was changing, that politicians were prepared to save more, the date could be postponed to 2010.
But I’m not expecting this change,” he said.
Debts are Growing
The debt of the state is constituted by the debts of the central government and is generated mainly by the accumulation of deficits in the state budget.
State debt is financed by treasury bills, annuity bills, direct loans or, for example, loans from the European Investment Bank.
The domestic debt of the state has so far increased this year from 38.5 billion to 719.4 billion crowns.
The state's external debt has so far increased this year from 1.7 billion kroner to 123.3 billion kroner.
The state debt called negotiable reached at the end of September 803.3 billion crowns and as of June it decreased by 13.7 billion crowns.
The average debt of the state amounted to 6.5 years.
“Total debt increased year-on-year from the first to the third half of the year by 13 percent, which is, given the current good health of the economy, a far too high figure.
It is interesting that the increase is generated mainly by annuity securities where it reaches 20 percent.
It is bad that the debt is growing, but on the other hand it indicates that there will be matter to negotiate when the pension reform comes,” commented the Pikora data.
Better than we expected
It follows the government's debt financing and management strategy for 2007 that the government had planned to borrow 159.2 billion crowns this year.
However, at the beginning of September, thanks to better-than-expected changes in state budget savings, the ministry reduced the projected amount to 152.8 billion crowns.
The sum is mainly constituted by the deficit of the state budget which will clearly reach 76 billion kroner this year, instead of the 91.3 billion kroner originally planned.
Then there are the maximum sources for the Czech Consolidation Agency, namely 13.3 billion kroner, the reserve of 10 billion for pension payments, the financing of government bonds for 43 billion kroner and repayments of loans from the European Investment Bank amounting to 1.8 billion kroner.
She was in court in Khartoum today for naming a teddy bear.
The British teacher tried in Sudan for insulting Islam was sentenced Thursday evening by a court in Khartoum to 15 days in prison and deportation, her lawyer said.
The British woman was accused of having allowed 6- to 7-year-old students to name a teddy bear Mohammed while any depiction of the prophet of Islam is illegal.
She was punished with a whiplash.
The 54-year-old British teacher, who works at the Unity High School in Khartoum, Sudan, was arrested Sunday at her home and charged under article 125 of the Sudanese Penal Code with Islam and sedition, following several complaints by parents of pupils to the Sudanese Ministry of Education.
The story actually goes back to September, when this teacher asked her students, aged 6/7, to choose a name for the teddy bear in the class.
“Eight names come out of the mouths of children, including Hassan, Abdullah and Mohammed,” says school principal Robert Boulos.
Finally, after a vote in the class, 20 out of 23 children chose Mohamed as their preferred first name.
Muhammad is of course the name of the Muslim prophet, but above all a very common name in Sudan.
The children then made a book for the class with the photo of the bear followed by the caption “My name is Mohamed”.
The bear itself did not carry any labels with that name, but the problem is simply that of the depiction of the prophet as an insult to Islam.
One of Gillian Gibbons’ Muslim colleagues, a teacher at the same school in Sudan, said he knew her well and that she would never have done anything that might be insulting to a religious faith, “I just regret that she asked children to vote for a name,” he said it was only an “innocent mistake.”
Opinion shared by many of the teacher’s students who describe her as “very attentive to her students” and “never talking about religion in class.”
Remember that the name Mohamed is also the second most given name in Britain, it is written in English in 14 different ways.
This name often chosen by Muslim families is a way of honoring the prophet (often given to the first child of a family).
But what are the rules regarding the use of this name?
Can you give it to a toy?
This is, of course, a question of interpretation.
