After more than 60 years of secrecy, the Nazi archives of Bad Arolsen, which trace the destinies of 17.5 million victims of the Hitler regime, are openly accessible.
The 47 million archival documents, stored on 27 km of line in Bad Arolsen (Hesse), were so far only available for "humanitarian" purposes, that is, individually and nominatively, at the request of a former victim or his heirs.
The eleven states in charge of their management - including Germany, France, Israel and the United States - agreed in May 2006 to open them to researchers and historians.
The process of ratification of this agreement by all States has been completed and the opening has been in effect since yesterday.
Sensitive Information
Historians' access to Bad Arolsen will allow research "including on prisoners' movements, camp population and the state of health of forced labour," said Reto Meistern, director of the archives managed by the International Committee of the Red Cross (ICRC).
Until recently, several States, including Germany, were opposed to the opening to the public of these nominative documents, due to the sensitive nature of certain information.
Such as the supposed homosexuality or mental disability of some victims of deportation.
The records of the concentration camps or arrest warrants issued by the Gestapo had been collected after the war for a practical purpose: to find civilians deported or subjected to compulsory work and, if necessary, to provide proof of their internment, in order to pave the way for their compensation.
Even today in Bad Arolsen, more than 300 permanent employees process tens of thousands of individual applications.
However, for some of the scientific community, access to Bad Arolsen is of limited interest.
“There is nothing fundamentally new to expect from these documents,” said Professor Wolfgang Benz, director of the Center for Research on Antisemitism at the Technische Universität Berlin in 2006.
