Which insurance is right for me?
Automobile insurance, which covers the driver in the event of possible accidents, involves a significant expense that will depend on various factors, such as age, gender, age of the driver's license, marital status, the type of vehicle to be insured or the use made of it, among others.
Having a car is the main thing.
Choosing the right car insurance is even more difficult than choosing the vehicle model.
And it is that, choosing the right auto insurance, is even more difficult than choosing the model of the vehicle.
Car insurance is an agreement between an insurance company and the insurer.
This compromise is materialized by an insurance contract, which establishes that the company receives the value of the premium granted and in return it becomes responsible for the obligation to pay compensation in the event of a claim.
The premium is the price of the insurance, which is established taking into account various factors, such as age, sex, seniority of the driver's license, marital status, the type of vehicle to be insured or the use made of it, among others.
Insurance companies set their prices on the basis of statistics, so that the higher the probability of an accident, the higher the odds to pay.
It is for this reason that people over the age of 25 and women have to pay lower premiums, since statistics show that these people have a lower claim rate due to their prudence.
Similarly, using censuses, companies have concluded that married people tend to have fewer accidents than single drivers.
The use of the vehicle will affect the frequency, and therefore the probability of having an accident.
By increasing the frequency, the probability increases.
There are many variables that insurers take into account when determining the price of the premium.
This is why the driver must study the situation carefully to choose the auto insurance that best suits his profile.
Here we will expose the most significant variables when choosing one or the other type of insurance, so that it, in addition to adapting to the characteristics of the insurer, offers him a reasonable price.
Young people under the age of 25 face a variety of disadvantages when it comes to contracting insurance at an affordable price, such as low driving experience and seniority of the driver's license.
While the ideal for being well insured is full-risk insurance, other, more economical options exist.
The most forward-thinking drivers can opt for all-risk insurance with deductible, so that they get insurance coverage at all-risk but at a more affordable price.
This form of agreement implies that the customer pays part of the amount of the claim.
"The part of the amount of the claim that the customer pays will be established based on the value of the premium, which will be higher the amount will be lower," Luis Noguera, the head in Spain of First Europa, online insurance broker, specifies.
Another option is extended third-party insurance, so that the customer provides protection to deal with damage caused to third parties, but by those caused on his own car.
In addition, it would be covered against theft, fire and loss of the vehicle.
One piece of advice.
If you are under 25 try to be careful and avoid claims as much as possible, since this will affect the bonus, which can reduce the price of insurance in the future.
A bonus is a reduction in the basic fare that the company owns.
On the contrary, a penalty is an increase in the basic tariff.
"The bonuses and sanctions will depend on the company and the profit of it.
If the company has had a good year it will be able to afford to increase the bonuses ", clarifies Noguera.
Beyond the age of 25, this becomes easier for drivers when they make a contract with an insurance, since the loss rate is reduced thanks to the accumulated experience.
It is for this reason that it is better to choose all-risk insurance with deductible.
“Normally young people cannot take advantage of the experience previously acquired after an accident,” said the director of the European company in Spain and adds that the majority of accidents occur during the second year of driving, once the ‘fear of the novice’ has passed.
However, if the client is married but does not yet have children, it is preferable that he negotiates insurance at all risk, as long as his economic situation allows it.
Marriages with children are considered by insurers to be the people with the lowest claim rate, because the surcharges will be lower.
In this case the best insurance would be an all-risk insurance with deductible (may be 300 euros), or an extended third-party insurance from the third year of life of the vehicle when the insured has a high level of bonus.
“They have a more relaxed driving and they have a greater purchasing power to allow themselves the luxury to assume a larger amount of franchises,” judges Luis Noguera.
For retirees, all-risk insurance with a deductible is preferable (this being 150 euros), or extended third-party insurance when the insurer has a high level of subsidy.
It must be said that motor insurance is something important, not only because it covers the driver in the face of possible accidents, but also because it represents a significant expense, that is why it is fundamental to properly study the insurance that suits us most according to our personal situation.
