The new gas deal between Russia and Ukraine is a wake-up call.
A dispute over the price of gas is fermenting between Ukraine and Russia, thus increasing the risk of repercussions on oil exports to Europe.
Most Russian gas exports to the European Union (EU) are carried by pipelines, and each pipeline is scrupulously monitored.
Kiev has announced that if Russia raises the cost of fuel, it will increase transit taxes to Russia.
Last year, an altercation between the two had caused a decrease in supplies to EU countries.
The latest dispute between Kiev and Moscow comes after the Ukrainian government and Gazprom, Russia’s gas-supplying monopoly, tried in vain to find an agreement on the cost of Russian gas supplied to Ukraine for the year 2008.
Gazprom said it would increase its prices to Ukraine as it agreed to pay for 2008, up to 50% more for the supply of gas from neighboring Turkmenistan.
Analysts said this would result in a 40 percent increase in the costs of imports from Gazprom for Ukraine.
“It is essential for us to use all our arguments during the talks, remembering that we are a country through which most of the gas passes,” Ukrainian Economy Minister Anatoly Kinkh told Reuters news agency.
“The fluctuations in gas costs would probably be related to our discussions about transit taxes (to Western Europe) via Ukraine.”
The last major altercation between Moscow and Kiev in January 2006 caused the interruption of Gazprom supplies to Ukraine.
This led to a drop in exports to Western Europe, thereby increasing prices.
Russian gas accounts for a quarter of the European Union's supplies.
Russia has the largest gas stockpiles, although most of them are still underdeveloped.
As a result, Gazprom completes its own supplies with gas from Turkmenistan and other nations of the former Soviet Union in Central Asia.
