Buses bring people back to work, and to fight al Qaeda.
The first bus full of Iraqi refugees from Syria arrived in Baghdad yesterday, dumping those exiles without money or visa renewals, or others still hoping that the city has returned to normal.
Some have returned to fight against the militants who have driven them away from their homes.
At the Mansour bus station, even before the arrival in Damascus of 800 people transported in convoys of dozens of official government buses, the terminal was filled with refugees from Syria and Jordan who returned by their means.
“I decided to go to Syria after they killed several doctors in Baghdad,” said Sabah al-Qubaisi, a Sunni doctor.
“I came home today because I saw on TV and read in the newspapers what happened in Baghdad and saw that the city is safer now.”
“They say the Mahdi army is no longer committing crimes!” he said, referring to the Shia militia of church activist Moqtada al-Sadr, who forced his men to step away for the time being.
Qassim al Atwani, a 38-year-old Shia teacher from the Sunni-dominated Amariyah area, returned with his two children because he could no longer renew his Syrian visa and because the regime is preventing Iraqis from working.
Shia's neighbors in Amariyah called him to inform him that the militia aided by the United States, allowed to drive Al Qaeda from the west of the capital, and invited him to return.
One of the newcomers from Jordan is the leader of a Sunni and Shia tribe who had to leave his home north of Baghdad because of a grenade attack after he incited citizens to rebel against al-Qaeda.
But he had to go home to fight.
“Two days ago, some of my friends called me and told me they had set up an anti-Al-Qaeda militia in Sleikh, and they needed me and my boys.”
“That’s why I’m coming home today,” said Sabaah Alu Obeidi, 62.
Many say they have attracted the capital’s growing calm since U.S. troops arrived, and the sight of continuing formation of well-armed “involved citizen groups” working with the U.S. military to defend their neighborhood.
But others say they were forced to return because of the visa problem and the decline of the capital of Damascus, where more than 1.3 million Iraqis have fled in recent years.
Salaam al-Samarrai, 51, a father of three, expressed suspicion about the exile visas that Prime Minister Nouri al-Maliki, who allegedly asked the Syrian government to limit to force people to return to the country.
More than two and a half million people reportedly fled the country because of sectarian death squads.
“We didn’t have a problem until al-Maliki came to Syria and urged the government to stop giving visas to Iraqis, to force them to return to Iraq,” Sunni said.
“I can’t trust a government that supports the criminals who burned down my house when I left.”
The decrease in violence can be partly explained by the fact that Sunnis were driven out of Shia areas and vice versa, creating places where tensions are lower.
There is concern that a sudden influx of refugees will again increase sectarian tensions and bring back fighting.
