Von Beust was criticized for canceling the Olympics.
The mayor's backlash from Hamburg's bid for the Summer Olympics has clashed in politics and the economy with virulent criticism.
Many want to keep fighting for the Water Games.
But von Beust calls for realism in the appraisal of chances.
Hamburg Chamber of Commerce chief Hans-Jörg Schmidt-Trenz on Wednesday described an abandonment as "bad for the local economy".
In recent times, no other project has deployed as many motivational forces in the city as the idea of the Olympics.
"Without this goal, the political-sports momentum could not have been maintained in the same measures."
Schmidt-Trenz urged the Senate not to bury the draft, but to find a new starting point in the longer term, "which takes as a starting point another modified agenda".
Mayor Ole von Beust said on Wednesday that Hamburg's Olympic ambitions were unrealistic until at least 2028.
"It is not Hamburg that decides on a bid for the Olympics, but the German Olympic Sports Federation," Von Beust told WELT ONLINE.
He refers to the expected decision of the Sports Federation at the beginning of December, regarding Munich's candidacy for the 2018 Winter Games.
This preference means for us that, in the timeframe we have planned until 2028, we will have no chance.”
However, the dream does not belong definitively to the past, said Von Beust.
The Hamburg Sports Federation (HSB) regretted Beust’s statements.
From this the impression would be given that Hamburg no longer wants to apply for the Olympics in the next 25 years.
“It’s too early to close an opportunity, burying the plans already now,” HSB President Günter Ploß said on Wednesday.
An abandonment of the candidacy would also be in contradiction with the statements of the head of the Senate on the occasion of the reception in plenary assembly of the German Federation of Higher Schools of Sport.
There, Von Beust allegedly described Hamburg's bid for the 2015 Universiade as "not a substitute" for the Hamburg Olympics.
The Federation of Higher Schools of Sport had first in the past weeks named Hamburg as the candidate city.
The SPD faction of the mayor has accused the Senate of not having used this precious time in building housing in Hamburg.
“The development of the Little Grasbrook was refused by the Senate for years because it played the Olympics card and excluded housing construction,” said SPD delegates Carola Veit and Jan Quast.
While the SPD has always called for the Little Grasbrook to have an integrated plan in the Olympics and a subsequent use of housing, the CDU would have relied exclusively on the "Event factor".
The candidacy for the 2012 Summer Olympics would have raised great enthusiasm in Hamburg.
Hamburg, however, had broken up against Leipzig.
These aren't Warhols' crates.
The one who connects the concepts Sweden and wooden case, thinks of Ikea, but not Andy Warhol.
Or is it?
At the moment, wooden crates made in Sweden cast shadows on Warhol’s list of works.
A large part of the ninety Brillo-Boxes of "Type Stockholm" listed there are counterfeits.
After the Swedish newspaper "Expressen" questioned a few months ago the authenticity of the Brillo-Boxes of the year 1968 by Andy Warhol, the internal researches of the Moderna Museet of Stockholm today lead to a disenchanting result: the six "Brillo-Boxes", of which the former director of the Pontus Hulten Museum gave a gift in 1995 to the International Brillo-Boxes of the year 1968 by Andy Warhol.
The ancient history is entangled, a disconcerting chain of artistic and curatorial productions.
In 1964, Warhol created in New York his first "Brillo-Boxes", painted wooden crates, which are based on the red-blue-white design of the "Brillo" powder soap cartons.
An exhibition of his work at the Moderna Museet in 1968 presented - with Warhol's agreement - hundreds of Brillo boxes made of cardboard: these did not come (for financial reasons) from Warhol, but had been delivered directly from the Brillo cardboard factory.
These were not works of art, but rather their models, exhibition samples.
At the same time, Warhol had given permission in 1968 to produce some Brillo wooden crates in Sweden, which were not exhibited at the Moderna Museet.
Witnesses of the time today speak of about fifteen wooden crates that at the time would have entered the history of art and auctions, as Brillo-Boxes original authorized by Andy Warhol, under the name "Type Stockholm".
Some of them reached more than $100,000 in auctions.
The problem now is that the legendary director of the Pontus Hultén Museum erroneously claimed later that about one hundred wooden crates had been produced and exhibited in Sweden in 1968, which Warhol would later cede to him.
In truth, Hultén’s 105 cases were produced in Malmö only in 1990, for an exhibition in St. Petersburg.
By that time, Warhol had been dead for three years.
Lars Byström, chief curator of the Moderna Museet, examined, alongside the six Brillo-Boxes of the museum, three other Swedish private collections, two of which were made in Stockholm in 1968: their laminate panels were first printed and sanded, then applied with a brush of white oil paint.
On the contrary, the texture of the copies dating back to 1990 reveals that the paint was applied directly without a background layer on the laminated panels, using a paint roller - moreover it is not an oil paint, but an acrylic.
"These crates have not been authorized by the artist and should be removed from the official list of Andy Warhol's Brillo-Boxes," hints the director of the Moderna Museet, Lars Nittve: "If the 'Andy Warhol Art Authentication Board' in New York doesn't come up with another decision, the Moderna Museet will classify the six crates in its collection."
Already in July, the Authentication Board announced that it would investigate the "heavy charges" that will be raised in the case of powdered soap boxes.
But since then there has been an inexorable silence.
The rebel soldiers of Manila give up
In the Philippines, rebel soldiers abandon, the same ones who had entrenched themselves in a hotel in Manila, and who had demanded the withdrawal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Chief Antonio Trillanes, who accused the President of corruption and electoral fraud, told reporters at the hotel that he could not answer for any bloodshed.
The loyal soldiers in power had shortly before stormed the hotel using tear gas.
The two dozen soldiers had been holed up in the building for hours.
About half of them were standing before the courts on Wednesday because of a failed coup attempt in 2003 - among them Trillanes.
He took advantage of the audience to suddenly overshadow himself with about 30 sympathizers.
The military police, who normally had to monitor them, had apparently deserted in his favor and joined his mutiny.
They broke into the Peninsula Hotel and demanded the removal of President Gloria Macapagal Arroyo.
Troops loyal to power closed the area around the respectable hotel.
The Chair convened an urgent meeting of the Security Cabinet.
National Security Adviser Norberto Gonzales condemned the soldiers' actions.
“People have had enough of it,” Trillanes said.
“We call on people to join us.”
General Danilo Lim, who was in command of the Scout Rangers' elite unit, said other army units would soon join the march.
Critics of the regime had called for a major demonstration against the president on Wednesday.
His government has been surrounded for months by accusations of corruption.
The financial district of Manila was already the scene of the attempted mutiny of about 200 members of the army against Arroyo since 2003.
The insurgency broke up almost 24 hours after the army refused to join.
Since 1986, there have been at least seven coup attempts against democratically elected governments in the Philippines.
